---
import SiteLayout from "../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "Texas Instruments (TXN) Intrinsic Value — Gemini's DCF Analysis",
  description: "An independent intrinsic value estimate for Texas Instruments (TXN) using a two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF) model, incorporating a cyclical normalized FCF approach.",
  category: "study",
  published: "2026-03-18",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  headline: meta.title,
  description: meta.description,
  datePublished: meta.published,
  author: {
    "@type": "Organization",
    name: "Gemini 2.5 Pro",
  },
};

// Financial Data (S&P Global Market Intelligence & Custom Analysis)
const currentPrice = 193.75;
const sharesOutstanding = 910; // in millions
const totalDebt = 14780; // in millions
const totalCash = 4880; // in millions
const normalizedBaseFCF = 6800; // in millions (Using Normalized approach due to massive 300mm fab CapEx cycle)

// Assumptions
const discountRate = 0.09; // 9.0% (WACC, based on 4.18% 10Yr Treasury, 0.98 Beta, high execution certainty)
const growthRate1to5 = 0.15; // 15.0% (Aggressive margin expansion and structural cost advantage when 300mm fabs hit scale)
const terminalGrowthRate = 0.035; // 3.5% (Sticky analog cycle, outpaces GDP)

// Year 1-5 Projections
const fcfProjections = [];
let currentFCF = normalizedBaseFCF;
let sumOfPV = 0;

for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
  currentFCF = currentFCF * (1 + growthRate1to5);
  const pvFactor = 1 / Math.pow(1 + discountRate, i);
  const pv = currentFCF * pvFactor;
  sumOfPV += pv;
  fcfProjections.push({
    year: i,
    fcf: currentFCF,
    pvFactor: pvFactor,
    pv: pv,
  });
}

// Terminal Value Math
const year5FCF = fcfProjections[4].fcf;
const terminalValue = (year5FCF * (1 + terminalGrowthRate)) / (discountRate - terminalGrowthRate);
const pvOfTerminalValue = terminalValue / Math.pow(1 + discountRate, 5);

// Final Enterprise & Equity Value
const enterpriseValue = sumOfPV + pvOfTerminalValue;
const totalEquityValue = enterpriseValue + totalCash - totalDebt;
const intrinsicValuePerShare = totalEquityValue / sharesOutstanding;

const marginOfSafety = ((intrinsicValuePerShare - currentPrice) / currentPrice) * 100;
const isUndervalued = intrinsicValuePerShare > currentPrice;

// Formatters
const fmtCurrency = (val) => `$${val.toFixed(2)}`;
const fmtMillions = (val) => `$${Math.round(val).toLocaleString()}M`;
const fmtPercent = (val) => `${(val * 100).toFixed(1)}%`;
const fmtPercentSigned = (val) => `${val > 0 ? "+" : ""}${(val).toFixed(2)}%`;

// Sensitivity Matrix
const sensitivityRates = [0.08, 0.085, 0.09, 0.095, 0.10];
const sensitivityGrowthRates = [0.025, 0.03, 0.035, 0.04, 0.045];

const sensitivityMatrix = sensitivityGrowthRates.map((g) => {
  return sensitivityRates.map((r) => {
    if (r <= g) return null; // Invalid DCF math
    const termVal = (year5FCF * (1 + g)) / (r - g);
    const pvTermVal = termVal / Math.pow(1 + r, 5);

    // Recalculate PV of FCFs for the new discount rate
    let tempSumPV = 0;
    for (let i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
      tempSumPV += fcfProjections[i - 1].fcf / Math.pow(1 + r, i);
    }

    const entVal = tempSumPV + pvTermVal;
    const eqVal = entVal + totalCash - totalDebt;
    return eqVal / sharesOutstanding;
  });
});
---

<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title={meta.title}
  description={meta.description}
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/texas-instruments-intrinsic-value"
  schema={schema}
>
  <article class="dcf-study">
    <header class="study-header">
      <div class="gemini-badge">Compiled by Gemini 2.5 Pro</div>
      <h1>Texas Instruments (TXN) Intrinsic Value</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">An independent two-stage DCF analysis of the analog semiconductor titan.</p>
    </header>

    <section class="verdict-card">
      <div class="verdict-header">Fair Value Estimate</div>
      <div class="verdict-price">{fmtCurrency(intrinsicValuePerShare)}</div>
      <div class="verdict-sub">PER SHARE</div>

      <div class="verdict-metrics">
        <div class="metric">
          <span class="label">CURRENT PRICE</span>
          <span class="value">{fmtCurrency(currentPrice)}</span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric">
          <span class="label">MARGIN OF SAFETY</span>
          <span class={`value ${isUndervalued ? 'positive' : 'negative'}`}>
            {fmtPercentSigned(marginOfSafety)}
          </span>
        </div>
        <div class="metric">
          <span class="label">VERDICT</span>
          <span class={`badge ${isUndervalued ? 'undervalued' : 'overvalued'}`}>
            {isUndervalued ? 'UNDERVALUED' : 'OVERVALUED'}
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="verdict-disclaimer">
        Based on FY2025 normalized actuals. Data via S&P Global (Mar 17, 2026).
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="thesis-section">
      <h2>The Thesis: Investing Through the Trough</h2>
      <p>
        Texas Instruments (TXN) is the undisputed king of analog and embedded processing chips.
        Currently, their reported Free Cash Flow is <strong>negative (-$300M in FY25)</strong>. To the untrained
        algorithmic screener, TXN looks like a distressed asset. <strong>To a strategic investor, it looks like a
        generational opportunity.</strong>
      </p>
      <p>
        TXN is intentionally sacrificing current cash flow to build massive 300mm wafer fabrication
        plants in Texas and Utah. These 300mm wafers are geometrically larger than legacy 200mm
        wafers, structurally reducing the cost per un-packaged chip by approximately 40%. Once these
        factories are fully online and depreciated over 10-15 years, TXN will possess a geopolitical and
        margin moat that competitors simply cannot replicate. We must value the business on its
        normalized cash-generating power, not its temporary construction bill.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="assumptions-section">
      <h2>My Assumptions & Rationale</h2>
      <div class="assumption-grid">
        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>Normalized Base FCF</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{fmtMillions(normalizedBaseFCF)}</div>
          <p class="assumption-rationale">
            <strong>Rationale:</strong> Because current FCF is negative due to $5B+ in CapEx, I am utilizing a normalized baseline. Historically, TXN routinely converts 35-40% of revenue into FCF. Applying this to current run-rate revenues yields a baseline structural cash generation of $6.8B per year once CapEx normalizes back to maintenance levels.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>FCF Growth Rate (Y1-Y5)</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{fmtPercent(growthRate1to5)}</div>
          <p class="assumption-rationale">
            <strong>Rationale:</strong> 15% growth from the normalized base. When the 300mm fabs scale production, the 40% structural cost advantage drops directly to the bottom line. Combined with the secular megatrend of analog chips required for every EV, industrial robot, and IoT device, the margin expansion lever is immense.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>Discount Rate (WACC)</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{fmtPercent(discountRate)}</div>
          <p class="assumption-rationale">
            <strong>Rationale:</strong> 9.0%. While the 10-Year Treasury is at 4.18%, TXN operates with low volatility (beta of 0.98). Their management team has arguably the best capital allocation track record in the S&P 500, having reduced share count by over 45% since 2004. This execution certainty demands a lower risk premium.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="assumption-card">
          <h3>Terminal Growth Rate</h3>
          <div class="assumption-value">{fmtPercent(terminalGrowthRate)}</div>
          <p class="assumption-rationale">
            <strong>Rationale:</strong> 3.5%. This outpaces standard 2% GDP inflation. Analog chips have incredibly long life-cycles (often 10-20 years for automotive/industrial parts). This sticky revenue and pricing power ensure growth beyond broader macroeconomic expansion.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="table-section">
      <h2>Discounted Cash Flow (DCF) Projections</h2>
      <p>Starting with our normalized base FCF of $6,800M, the table below projects 5 years of aggressive cash generation as the CapEx cycle ends, discounted back to Present Value (PV) using a 9.0% WACC.</p>

      <div class="table-container">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Period</th>
              <th>Projected FCF</th>
              <th>PV Factor ({fmtPercent(discountRate)})</th>
              <th>Present Value</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {fcfProjections.map((row) => (
              <tr>
                <td>Year {row.year}</td>
                <td class="num">{fmtMillions(row.fcf)}</td>
                <td class="num">{row.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
                <td class="num">{fmtMillions(row.pv)}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
            <tr class="total-row">
              <td colspan="3">Sum of PV of FCFs (Years 1-5)</td>
              <td class="num highlight">{fmtMillions(sumOfPV)}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="table-section">
      <h2>Terminal & Final Valuation Math</h2>
      <p>The Terminal Value captures all future cash flows from Year 6 onward into perpetuity.</p>

      <div class="table-container calc-table">
        <table>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Year 5 FCF</td>
              <td class="num">{fmtMillions(year5FCF)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Terminal Value Calculation</td>
              <td class="num">({fmtMillions(year5FCF)} * {1 + terminalGrowthRate}) / ({discountRate} - {terminalGrowthRate})</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>Terminal Value</td>
              <td class="num">{fmtMillions(terminalValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="total-row">
              <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
              <td class="num highlight">{fmtMillions(pvOfTerminalValue)}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <p class="mt-8">Assembling the final equity value per share, adjusting for TXN's current net debt position (driven by fab construction borrowing):</p>

      <div class="table-container calc-table">
        <table>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Sum of PV of FCFs (Years 1-5)</td>
              <td class="num">{fmtMillions(sumOfPV)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>+ PV of Terminal Value</td>
              <td class="num">{fmtMillions(pvOfTerminalValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="subtotal-row">
              <td>= Enterprise Value</td>
              <td class="num">{fmtMillions(enterpriseValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>+ Net Cash (Cash - Debt)</td>
              <td class="num">{fmtMillions(totalCash - totalDebt)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="subtotal-row">
              <td>= Total Equity Value</td>
              <td class="num">{fmtMillions(totalEquityValue)}</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td>÷ Shares Outstanding</td>
              <td class="num">{sharesOutstanding}M</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="final-row">
              <td>Intrinsic Value Per Share</td>
              <td class="num highlight-gold">{fmtCurrency(intrinsicValuePerShare)}</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sensitivity-section">
      <h2>Sensitivity Matrix</h2>
      <p>How does the fair value change if interest rates stay higher for longer (increasing the discount rate) or if secular analog growth slows?</p>

      <div class="table-container sensitivity-table">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th rowspan="2" class="corner">Terminal<br/>Growth</th>
              <th colspan="5" class="center">Discount Rate (WACC)</th>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              {sensitivityRates.map(r => <th class="center">{fmtPercent(r)}</th>)}
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {sensitivityGrowthRates.map((g, rowIdx) => (
              <tr>
                <th class="side-header">{fmtPercent(g)}</th>
                {sensitivityMatrix[rowIdx].map((val, colIdx) => {
                  if (!val) return <td class="num invalid">N/A</td>;
                  const margin = (val - currentPrice) / currentPrice;
                  let cellClass = "neutral";
                  if (margin > 0.15) cellClass = "undervalued-cell";
                  else if (margin < -0.15) cellClass = "overvalued-cell";

                  // Highlight the base case cell
                  const isBaseCase = (g === terminalGrowthRate && sensitivityRates[colIdx] === discountRate);

                  return (
                    <td class={`num ${cellClass} ${isBaseCase ? 'base-case' : ''}`}>
                      {fmtCurrency(val)}
                    </td>
                  );
                })}
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <div class="sensitivity-legend">
          <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot under"></span> Undervalued (&gt;15% Margin)</span>
          <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot base"></span> Fair Value</span>
          <span class="legend-item"><span class="dot over"></span> Overvalued (&lt;-15% Margin)</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="risks-section">
      <h2>Risks & Bear Case</h2>
      <p>A rigorous DCF requires stress-testing the thesis. Here is what could break the valuation:</p>

      <div class="risk-card">
        <h3>1. The China De-risking Problem</h3>
        <p>TXN historically derived immense revenue from the Chinese industrial and automotive markets. As China subsidizes local legacy and analog chipmakers to insulate their supply chains, TXN could face a structural, permanent loss of market share in the world's largest EV market.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-card">
        <h3>2. Prolonged CapEx Cycle</h3>
        <p>My model assumes the massive capital expenditure pipeline tapers off within the next 24-36 months, allowing FCF to explode upward. If factory build-outs are delayed, face cost overruns, or if TXN decides they need even more capacity, the "normalization" of cash flow gets pushed further into the future, destroying present value.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-card">
        <h3>3. "Lower for Longer" Utilization</h3>
        <p>Building 300mm fabs only creates a margin advantage if the factories run at high utilization rates. If the industrial semiconductor downcycle is protracted and end-demand remains weak, the fixed costs of these massive empty factories will severely compress margins.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Why did Gemini use a 'Normalized FCF' approach for Texas Instruments?</summary>
        <div class="faq-content">
          <p>Texas Instruments is currently in the middle of a massive, multi-year capital expenditure cycle to build 300mm wafer fabrication plants. This has temporarily driven their reported Free Cash Flow into negative territory (-$300M in FY25). Valuing a structurally profitable, cyclical company at the trough of its investment cycle using current FCF yields an inaccurate result. Gemini used a normalized baseline FCF of $6.8B, representing the true cash-generating power of the business once the CapEx normalizes.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What growth rate was applied to Texas Instruments' DCF?</summary>
        <div class="faq-content">
          <p>Gemini aggressively assigned a 15% FCF growth rate for Years 1-5. This accounts for the incredible operating leverage that will kick in once the new 300mm fabs are fully operational, driving massive margin expansion and structural cost advantages.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What discount rate was used for TXN?</summary>
        <div class="faq-content">
          <p>A 9.0% discount rate (WACC) was used, grounded in the CAPM utilizing a 4.18% 10-Year Treasury rate and a beta of 0.98. Texas Instruments' legendary capital allocation and shareholder returns justify this slightly lower-than-average risk premium.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>

    <footer class="study-footer">
      <p><strong>Disclaimer:</strong> The numbers presented on this page are for educational and entertainment purposes only. They are the result of a deterministic mathematical model fed with assumptions generated by an Artificial Intelligence (Gemini 2.5 Pro). This does not constitute investment advice. Always conduct your own due diligence before investing in the stock market.</p>
    </footer>
  </article>
</SiteLayout>

